[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] Stewart*** was a 19th-century Sandy Hook pilot boat built in 1865 at the Edward F.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] Williams shipyard to replace the pilot boat *George Steers,* which was lost in 1865.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] She was built for the New Jersey and New York Sandy Hook Pilots Association.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] The *Stewart* was in a collision with the steamship *Scotia* and sank in 1869.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] She was replaced by the *James Gordon Bennett* in 1870.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] 6, was launched from the shipyard of Edward F.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] Williams, at Greenpoint, Brooklyn, on October 11, 1865.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] She was the twelfth vessel of her class built by Williams in the last ten years.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] She was built for pilots of the New Jersey and Sandy Hook Pilots' Association.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] She was built to replace the *George Steers,* No.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] At the launch and naming ceremony, Ellen M.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] Clark, did the christening by breaking a bottle of champagne over the bow.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] The name of the boat was nominated by the friends of Alexander Turney Stewart, the dry goods millionaire businessman.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] Stewart,* was registered as a pilot Schooner with the *Record of American and Foreign Shipping,* from 1871 to 1874.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] Her owners were the Pilots' Association; built-in 1865 at Greenpoint, New York; and her hailing port was the Port of New York.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] Her dimensions were 80 ft. in length; 21 ft. breadth of beam; 7.10 ft. depth of hold; and 90-tons Tonnage.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] Stewart,* was in a collision with the Delaware schooner *Transit,* twenty miles east of Cape May Lightship.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] The *Stewart* was towed into port and reported damages in the sum of $5,000.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] On April 9, 1869, a collision case for the *A.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] Stewart* was brought before the United States District Court.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] The case was Chapman vs. the Schooner *Transit*.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] The court ruled that both boats were equally responsible for the collision and should share the cost for damages.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] The court also made the decision to remove the wreck of the *A.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] Stewart,* from the channel outside Sandy Hook.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] Stewart* sank when she came in collision with the steamship *Scotia* off Sandy Hook, New Jersey.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] The pilots and crew were saved and brought to port.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/a-t-stewart-pilot-boat] Stewart* was lost in 1869, the *James Gordon Bennett*, No.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Captain **Alfred Bulltop Stormalong** was an American folk hero and the subject of numerous nautical-themed tall tales originating in Massachusetts.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong was said to be a sailor and a giant, some 30 feet (9.1 m) tall; he was the master of a huge clipper ship known in various sources as either the *Courser* or the *Tuscarora*, a ship purportedly so tall that it had hinged masts to avoid catching on the Moon.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The name of Stormalong first appeared in a cycle of sea shanties that Stan Hugill, in his *Sea Shanties of the Seven Seas*, traces back to African-American folk songs of the 1830s and '40s.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Bearing names like "Mister Stormalong", "Way Stormalong John", and "Yankee John, Stormalong", these sailors' work songs generally featured praise for a deceased seaman and for his benevolent son.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The tall tales about Stormalong first appeared in the 1911 book *Here's Audacity!* by Frank Shay.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] More tales appeared in the 1933 pamphlet *Old Stormalong Yarns* by C.E.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] New England was where he was beached as a baby, already three fathoms (18 ft) tall.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] According to one telling, he outgrew Cape Cod and moved to Boston, where he signed aboard the first ship that would take him at the age of twelve.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] He had a lifelong rivalry with a Kraken, a huge sea monster from Norse myth; in fact, the Kraken escaped from him in their first encounter, causing a dejected Stormalong to abandon the sea life for life as a farmer somewhere in the Midwest.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Some sources say he had a ship so large that a stable of Arabian horses were aboard for his crew to get from one end of the ship to the other.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Among other things, the ship Alfred was best said to have drilled the course of the Panama Canal by slamming into the Panamanian coast, and to have gotten stuck in the English Channel, which required the crew to grease the ship's hull with soap.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The soap combined with the scraping of the hull against the Gray Cliffs of Dover turned them bright white.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] As Stormalong grew older, he eventually encountered the Kraken again, this time successfully drawing the beast into a whirlpool from which it never escaped.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The aged Stormalong won the race by several miles, but the stress of handling the wheel through the difficult Atlantic crossing killed him.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong was buried at sea, and Davy Jones himself opened his famous locker to accept Stormalong's body.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Another ending to his life is as follows: While Stormalong was on his Caribbean adventures, he passed by Florida, seeing that there was a tremendous hurricane that tore through his ship.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Ships sailing nearby were being tossed around by the heavy waves.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong went overboard and piled as many boats as he could onto his ship.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] When the storm finally wound down, the sailors were dropped back off at Florida.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] After that, he went back on board, unfurling the sails of his ship, seeing if they could be repaired.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] A great wind, the last blow of the hurricane, hit the sails, lifting Stormalong and his ship into the sky.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] A third ending to his life takes advantage of the inference that, being a giant, Alfred Bulltop Stormalong was an enormous eater.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] It describes a time when his hunger was greater than usual and led him to eat so much food (one variant cites a breakfast of six sharks; it is not definitely known what other variants exist) that he suffered terminal indigestion, causing his magnificent appetite to finish him.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/ambassador-clipper] William Walker built *Ambassador* at Lavender Dry Dock in London.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/ambassador-clipper] Though considered a fast ship, *Ambassador* was said to be "very cranky and overmasted".
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/ambassador-clipper] Her first passage to the UK from Fuzhou came during the Tea Race of 1870 under Captain Duggan and took 115 days, a mediocre performance; that same year the fastest tea passage, also from Fuzhou, was made by the clipper *Lahloo* in just 98 days.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/ambassador-clipper] *Ambassador*'s fastest passage between China and England was 108 days, in 1872.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/ambassador-clipper] The wreck is now reduced to a skeletal frame.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The ***Andrew Jackson*** was a 1,679-registered-ton medium clipper built by the firm of Irons & Grinnell in Mystic, Connecticut in 1855.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The vessel was designed for the shipping firm of J.H.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] Brower & Co. to carry cargo intended for sale to participants in the California Gold Rush.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The ship was 220 feet (67 m) in length, had a beam of 41 ft., 2 in., and a draft 22 ft., 3 in.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The vessel was described as "a very handsome, well-designed ship.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] This was one of only three 89-day runs performed by square-rigged ships driving from New York City to California.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The other two runs were both posted by *Flying Cloud*.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] *Flying Cloud*'s fastest New York-to-California run had taken 89 days and 8 hours; *Andrew Jackson*'s run was, by four hours, widely acclaimed in the newspapers as the fastest in history.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] Some clipper ship authorities, including Howe and Matthews, assert that *Andrew Jackson* did not actually set the record described above.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] They concede, however, that this medium clipper, perhaps not naturally as fast as *Flying Cloud*, achieved a remarkable passage as the result of a combination of hard driving by the captain and favorable winds.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] However, after careful scrutiny of the logbooks, one author, Carl C.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] Cutler, concludes that a case can be made for either *Flying Cloud* or *Andrew Jackson* holding the record.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] Some will consider the passage from pilot-to-pilot as the appropriate indicator of fastest sailing performance around Cape Horn.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] *Flying Cloud* holds the record time for a passage anchor-to-anchor from New York to San Francisco, of 89 days 8 hours, while *Andrew Jackson'*s completed passage anchor-to-anchor may have been as long as 89 days 20 hours.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] The schooner ***Anglona*** was the first American opium clipper.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] She sailed in the Chinese coastal trade in the 1840s, and had a famous race with the schooner *Ariel* around Lintin Island.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] Forbes was interested in fast schooners for clipper and coastal service in China.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] The first clipper which Forbes sent to China, the *Rose*, foundered in the July typhoon of 1841.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] Forbes purchased *Anglona* at Brown & Bell's New York yard for Russell & Co. for use as a despatch boat between Hong Kong, Macao, and Whampoa.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] Other American pilot boat models sent to China in the 1840s included the *Zephyr* and the *Spec*, also built on the New York model.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] Shortly after Shanghai opened to foreign trade, three Boston pilot boats were sent: the 90 ton *Golden Gate*, the 90 ton *Siren*, and the 75 ton *Daniel Webster*, which served as pilot boats in the Yangtze River.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] Within two weeks of purchase, *Anglona* sailed for China under Captain Turner.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] She arrived at Cape Horn in 61 days, and Java Head in 95 days.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] Russell & Co put *Anglona* in service on the Canton River until the new treaty ports opened, at which time she was put in the coastal trade.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] Captain Turner did not serve long, as he was knocked overboard by the mainboom during a sudden jibe, and drowned.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] In 1843, *Anglona* was under command of Capt.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] Adamson; in 1844 she was under Captain Macfarlane.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] On September 20, 1841, *Anglona* left Hong Kong with a 108-ton cargo of rice from Macao bound for the East Coast; on Dec.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] 2, she left Hong Kong with a 108-ton cargo from Macao of opium or specie bound for Namoa.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] Lee, the designer of the *Rose*, wanted to know why Forbes hadn't come to him for a clipper schooner instead, and got Forbes to agree to taking a half interest in one of his schooners if it could beat the *Anglona*.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] The *Ariel*, a new 92-ton schooner built by Sprague & James at Medford, MA was taken out for a trial in 1841 out of Lewis Wharf in Boston Harbor, against the 30 ton schooner-yacht *Breeze*, which had been built for Forbes by Daniel C.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] The wind had freshened and was blowing in hard puffs.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] He had suggested taking in a second reef, but his companions assured him the wind would slacken as they approached the harbor.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] In stays off Sound Point Beacon, the Ariel laid down before she could get way on for a tack towards Long Island, and sank in seven fathoms of water.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] When *Ariel* was refloated, Lee agreed to reduce the rig, and cut down the masts as per Forbes’ suggestion.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] *Ariel* was then sent to China under Capt.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] Poor, making an 80-day passage to Anjer.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] The race between *Ariel* and *Anglona* was about 40 mi., from Macao Roads around Lintin and back, for stakes of $1,000 and Forbes’ agreement to take half-interest in *Ariel* if she won.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] *Anglona* was much stronger sailing to windward, due to the shallow draft of *Ariel,* and took the lead until rounding the island.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] At that point, *Ariel* set a large flying square sail and topsail.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/anglona-clipper] *Anglona* had no ballooning sails for running downwind, and was beaten by 17 minutes.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/antelope-of-boston] The hull was black, the inside dark buff with blue waterways.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/antelope-of-boston] In 1853, *Antelope* arrived in San Francisco from New York under Captain Snow on August 31 after a passage of 128 days, returning to New York via Callao in 178 days.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/antelope-of-boston] After one more round trip to the West Coast of South America *Antelope* went into the China trade.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/antelope-of-boston] In July 1858, *Antelope* departed Bangkok for China under Captain Clarke.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/antelope-of-boston] On August 6, she struck on Discovery Shoal, Paracels Reef, which was not visible due to a high, ending her sailing career after six years and nine months.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Captain Clarke, four passengers, and 13 seamen abandoned ship, and set out in one of the ship's boats.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/antelope-of-boston] A second boat, which became separated during the night, carried the mate, one seaman, and ten Chinese passengers.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Four days later, a Chinese fishing junk came into view.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Clarke offered the fishermen $20 for a tow to a place where water could be had.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Once the *Antelope* party was taken in tow, it became evident that the fishermen were not trustworthy.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Fearing piracy, the shipwrecked party cut the tow rope and attempted an escape.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/antelope-of-boston] The fishermen pursued the boat, attacked it with stones, and finally set two fishermen to stand guard with spears while the others robbed the *Antelope* party.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/antelope-of-boston] In the midst of the confusion, two of the *Antelope* sailors took advantage of the distraction and boarded the fishing junk, dispatching its crew.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/antelope-of-boston] Captain Clarke also attempted to board the junk, but fell in the water and had to be rescued.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/antelope-of-boston] The shipwrecked *Antelope* party then took command of the junk, and arrived in Hong Kong on August 14.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/ariel-clipper] A premium was paid for the first consignment of tea to reach London in each season.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/ariel-clipper] The clipper *Fiery Cross* left Fuzhou on 29 May and *Ariel*, *Taeping* and *Serica* on the 30th.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/ariel-clipper] On 6 September *Taeping* docked twenty minutes ahead of *Ariel*, and about two hours ahead of *Serica*.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/ariel-clipper] *Fiery Cross* and *Taitsing* arrived two days later.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/ariel-clipper] After 99 days and almost 16,000 miles (26,000 km) the leaders were still tied and raced within sight of each other the full length of the English Channel and into the Thames.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/ariel-clipper] *Taeping*, under Captain McKinnon, drew less water and was able to tie up in the London docks twenty minutes ahead of *Ariel*, under Captain Keay.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/ariel-clipper] *Taeping* divided her winnings of 10 shillings per ton with the owners of *Ariel* and Captain McKinnon divided the captain's £100 with Captain Keay, who hailed from Anstruther.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/ariel-clipper] With the completion of the Suez Canal the tea trade was taken over by steamships and most of the clippers transferred to the Australian trade, carrying general cargo to either Sydney or Melbourne, and returning with wool — for which a premium price was also paid on the first shipments of the season.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/blue-jacket-clipper] The frame of *Blue Jacket* was white oak, with planking and ceiling of hard pine.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/blue-jacket-clipper] She was diagonally braced with iron, and square-fastened throughout.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/blue-jacket-clipper] The interior finish work was quite elegant, according to a contemporary description in the U.S.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/blue-jacket-clipper] The *Blue Jacket* was chartered by the White Star Line in 1854.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/blue-jacket-clipper] The passengers and crew of the burning vessel were divided into three boats, one cutter and two lifeboats.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/blue-jacket-clipper] The three boats separated after two days.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/blue-jacket-clipper] There is no record of the two lifeboats, but on March 16, the barque *Pyrmont* of Hamburg rescued the crew on board the cutter.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/blue-jacket-clipper] There were nine survivors, who managed to guard £15,000 worth of gold from the ship.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/blue-jacket-clipper] After the loss of the ship, "the figurehead of the *Blue Jacket* was found washed up on the shore of the Rottnest Island, off Fremantle, Western Australia".
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/blue-jacket-clipper] The figurehead washed ashore 21 months later, roughly 6,000 miles (9,700 km) from the location where *Blue Jacket* burned – 53°S 60°W﻿ / ﻿53°S 60°W﻿ / -53; -60.
[src:blue-jacket-clipper/blue-jacket-clipper] The average speed of drift for the figurehead was calculated to be 6½ miles per day.
